title: For Sale:  Upgraded Arsenal SLR 107 CR
location: Apex, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
For sale is a Arsenal SLR 107 CR with a low round count in excellent condition. I bought this weapon as a home defense gun, but my girlfriend was never really confortable with the AK platform so I switched to a different rifle. This is a Bulgarian made new production gun with a cold hammer forged barrel and factory side folding stock, nothing but the best. The 107CR has a gas block with integrated front sight, reducing the swing weight of the AK, making it quicker to target. It has a faux conical recoil booster that covers up the 16 inch barrel, but if you want to remove the booster I threaded the barrel to accept a muzzle device (standard AK threads). I changed the sights for meprolight tritium sights, they were installed a year ago so the tritium is very bright. The weapon has a Solar Tac MFER mag well, which helps speed reloads up considerably by propperly aligning your mags during changes. I changed out the pistol grip for a US palm grip, which helps you get better leverage on the gun than the standard AK grip to more easily manipulate the weapon. I also installed a Krebs custom safety lever, which has a bolt hold open notch and allows for one handed manipulation of the safety. The front forend was replaced with a Russian made grip, which has 1913 rails for adding a light. I worked very hard to keep the weight down, unloaded this rifle is only 7 and a half pounds, it has very little recoil in firing and is already set up to be the ultimate fighting Kalashnikov. This is the real deal, not some cheapo WASR with some Tapco crap bolted on to look cool, this gun will carry you through the Apocalypse.

If you would like, I also have a Russian made PK-A sight for sale that I will sell for 250$ in addition to the cost of the rifle. The gun will come with the original 5 round factory magazine, but if you need more mags with the gun let me know, I have a ton of AK mags of various types and I will cut you a deal on the mags of your choice.

postcontent:
This is a beautiful example of these rifles.  Most these days are missing various pieces, usually the rear sling mount or the folding portion of the sight.  This one is in better shape than others I have seen, but I haven't seen many.  This one still has a light honey color to the stock.  These were originally produced starting in 1891 and on through WW2.  This is Italian (Beretta) made, and this one I believe was made in 1940, and is still in the original caliber.  The Caliber is 6.5 x 52 (Carcano)  Ammo is still in production.  It uses a 6 shot En Block clip similar to a Mannlicher Clip.  I have one of these clips and maybe 1.5 boxes of ammo that I will throw in with.  Bore is in good shape and I was able to get about a 6" group at 100 yards.  Some cleaning of the bore may improve that.  Using better ammunition would make a vast improvement also.  This is the Carbine model, and as far as I can tell is the original 38 design.  Carcano Rifles have a rich history, and is also the model rifle used in the Kennedy Assassination.

Asking $375OBO due to condition and rarity.  Open to trades.  I have other listings and am open to many to one trades, and one to many.  Take a look at my other listings using link at top.  

I prefer email for first contact.  tvise  at  visetech.net   If unable to email text or call 864-384-704one

title: For Sale:  Trijicon Acog Ta31f----$700
location: EVERYWHERE IN NC, Greensboro, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have a brand new Trijicon Acog Ta31f. $700 has not been shot with yet. Brand new just not my cup of tea. 
_______________________________________________________________________

Sound too good to be true? Probably is. 

BE CAREFUL BUYING OPTICS SECOND HAND ON ARMSLIST, CRAIGSLIST AND EVEN AT GUN SHOWS!!!

There are very, very "similar" knockoffs of AIMPOINT, TRIJICON, and EOTECH that are BEING made by foreign companies. They look just like the similar thing, and you might not even be able to tell the difference holding them side by side. It's to the point where they are getting scarily close at reproducing the look and feel of a product. 

However, the quality of the functional components will always be off. Trijicon Acogs, for instance, will not have tritium in it and will not glow in the dark like the real ones. 

Buy from a reputable dealer, ask for a serial number before buying, bring your real one for comparison, etc. Do whatever it takes but, whatever you do, be very, very careful.
